The Company has deployed third-party blockchain analytics tooling to support transaction monitoring and origin/destination analysis. The Company shall ensure that:

(i) The vendor tool is configured to detect attribution against the Company's defined risk policies;

(ii) Alerts generated by the tool are subject to human review by AML/CFT/CPF personnel before disposition;

(iii) The Company maintains a documented record of vendor rule configurations, alert thresholds, and override decisions;

(iv) The Company periodically validates vendor coverage against its risk assessment.

The Company shall ensure that, in the absence of third-party blockchain analytics tooling, the transaction monitoring framework relies on:

(i) Public blockchain explorers and address-attribution sources;

(ii) Documented manual review procedures for high-value, cross-border, or otherwise flagged transactions;

(iii) Periodic engagement with industry forums and FIU-IND red-flag indicator publications to remain current on typologies;

(iv) Board-level review of the adequacy of the current monitoring approach and consideration of vendor adoption as transaction volume and complexity grow.

#### 12.2.2 Scope of Transaction Monitoring (Paragraph 5.2.2)

The Company shall be able to flag any unusual or suspicious movement of funds or activity that may indicate potential illicit behaviour or activity, including across the following transaction types:

(a) Fiat-to-fiat transactions;

(b) Virtual-to-virtual transactions (i.e., VDA-to-VDA);

(c) Fiat-to-virtual transactions (i.e., fiat-to-VDA);

(d) Virtual-to-fiat transactions (i.e., VDA-to-fiat).

#### 12.2.3 Proportionality and Calibration (Paragraph 5.2.2)

The Transaction Monitoring programme shall be appropriate to the scale and size of the Company and the products and services it provides.

The Company shall put in place appropriate systems that incorporate:

(a) Red-flag indicators (RFIs) issued by FIU-IND from time to time;

(b) Guidance issued by FIU-IND from time to time;

(c) Typologies published by FIU-IND from time to time;

(d) Instructions issued by FIU-IND from time to time;

(e) Any additional indicators identified by the Company through its own risk assessment (as set out in Section 8.1 of this Policy).

#### 12.2.4 Alert Review and STR Filing (Paragraph 5.2.2)

All alerts generated through the Transaction Monitoring system shall be reviewed by the AML/CFT/CPF monitoring team and the Principal Officer without delay.

Where applicable, Suspicious Transaction Reports (STRs) shall be filed promptly with FIU-IND in accordance with Section 15 of this Policy.

Alert disposition shall be documented, including reasons for closure of an alert without filing of an STR, and shall be retained as part of the Company's records in accordance with Section 16 of this Policy.

#### 12.2.5 Systems for Transaction Data Storage and Reconstruction (Paragraph 5.2.3)

In accordance with Paragraph 5.2.3 of the 2026 Guidelines and Rule 4 of the PML Rules, the Company shall deploy appropriate, scalable, and secure systems to enable storage of transaction data so as to permit reconstruction of individual transactions.

These systems shall:

(a) Integrate seamlessly with existing systems of the Company;

(b) Provide role-based access control;

(c) Maintain reliable data backup and recovery mechanisms;

(d) Preserve audit trails (including timestamps and authentication logs) in a tamper-proof manner, consistent with Section 16 of this Policy.

Given the Company's hot-wallet-only custody model, transaction data storage and reconstruction systems shall additionally:

(i) Capture wallet-level transaction logs in real time, including key rotation events and authorisation logs;

(ii) Maintain synchronised records between hot wallet activity and the corresponding client account transaction records, enabling end-to-end reconstruction of any single transaction;

(iii) Implement appropriate cryptographic-key custody safeguards consistent with the Company's information security and CERT-In Cyber Security Audit obligations.

Given the Company's combined hot and cold wallet custody model, transaction data storage and reconstruction systems shall additionally:

(i) Capture transaction logs for both hot and cold wallet movements, including all movements between hot and cold wallet pools;

(ii) Maintain reconciliation records between aggregate cold-storage holdings and the aggregate of client account balances backed by such cold storage;

(iii) Implement enhanced key management and segregation-of-duties controls for cold wallet operations, with documented procedures for cold-to-hot transfer authorisations;

(iv) Where cold custody is provided by a third-party custodian, maintain documented operational arrangements addressing AML/CFT/CPF data access, transaction-record availability, and incident-response coordination;

(v) Ensure that transaction monitoring rules cover both retail customer wallet movements and treasury-level cold-to-hot reallocations to detect anomalous internal transfers.

Given the Company's non-custodial operating model, the Company recognises that its custody position is structurally distinct from traditional VDA SPs:

(i) Customer funds are held in self-custodial wallets controlled by the customers themselves, not by the Company;

(ii) Notwithstanding the non-custodial model, the Company's AML/CFT/CPF obligations under PMLA, PML Rules, and the 2026 Guidelines remain applicable to the activities the Company facilitates, including any VDA exchange, swap, transfer-routing, or financial service activity;

(iii) Transaction monitoring systems shall be configured to capture all transactions the Company facilitates, even where the Company does not directly hold customer funds, including the wallet addresses involved, transaction hashes, and counterparty information;

(iv) The Company shall apply heightened transaction monitoring scrutiny to flows involving customer-controlled self-custody wallets and unhosted wallet counterparties, in accordance with Section 17.2 of this Policy and Paragraph 7.2 of the 2026 FIU-IND Guidelines;

(v) The Company shall ensure that its non-custodial design does not, in operational practice, become a means of evading CDD, sanctions screening, or Travel Rule obligations where these would otherwise apply to its facilitated activities.

#### 12.2.6 Risk Scoring and Automation (Paragraph 5.2.4)

In light of the large volumes of transactions carried out on a continuous basis, the Company may employ:

(a) Transaction risk scoring models;

(b) Automated systems for monitoring;

(c) Artificial intelligence (AI) and machine learning (ML) technologies, where appropriate, to support effective monitoring.

The deployment of any automated or AI/ML system shall be subject to:

(i) Pre-deployment risk assessment in accordance with Section 8.1 of this Policy;

(ii) Periodic validation of model outputs;

(iii) Human review of all alerts and final decisions remaining with the Principal Officer or designated AML personnel;

(iv) Documented governance and version control over models and rule sets.

#### 12.2.7 Indicative Transaction Monitoring Categories

Without prejudice to the FIU-IND red-flag indicators, guidance, typologies, and instructions issued from time to time (which the Company shall follow as binding), the Company's Transaction Monitoring programme shall, at a minimum, address the following indicative categories:

(a) **Velocity-based monitoring:** Unusual transaction frequency or count relative to the client's risk profile and historical baseline;

(b) **Value-based monitoring:** Transactions of size inconsistent with the client's declared income, occupation, or business activity;

(c) **Counterparty risk monitoring:** Transactions involving counterparties associated with sanctioned addresses, mixer/tumbler addresses, or addresses associated with known illicit activity;

(d) **Structuring patterns:** Transactions that appear designed to fall below reporting thresholds or to obscure the true scale of activity;

(e) **Unhosted wallet transactions:** Transfers to or from unhosted (self-custodial) wallets, in accordance with Paragraph 7.2 of the 2026 Guidelines and Section 17 of this Policy;

(f) **AEC and mixer-related activity:** Any attempted dealings in Anonymity-Enhancing Crypto Tokens, mixers, or tumblers, in accordance with Paragraphs 7.4 and 7.5 of the 2026 Guidelines and Section 17 of this Policy;

(g) **Onboarding-stage anomalies:** Liveness detection failures, geo-location mismatches, suspicious onboarding patterns (e.g., multiple onboardings from same IP or device), and failed CDD verifications;

(h) **Behavioural deviations:** Material changes in a client's transaction pattern compared to their historical baseline, including dormant accounts reactivating with unusually large or atypical activity.
